# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: linear-regression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In statistics, the **coefficient of determination**, denoted *R*2 or *r*2 and pronounced "R squared", is the proportion of the variation in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable(s).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] It is a statistic used in the context of statistical models whose main purpose is either the prediction of future outcomes or the testing of hypotheses, on the basis of other related information.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] It provides a measure of how well observed outcomes are replicated by the model, based on the proportion of total variation of outcomes explained by the model.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] There are several definitions of *R*2 that are only sometimes equivalent.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In simple linear regression (which includes an intercept), *r*2 is simply the square of the sample *correlation coefficient* (*r*), between the observed outcomes and the observed predictor values.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] If additional regressors are included, *R*2 is the square of the *coefficient of multiple correlation*.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In both such cases, the coefficient of determination is always smaller than 1 and usually greater than 0.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Cases where *R*2 is negative can arise when the predictions that are being compared to the corresponding outcomes have not been derived from a model-fitting procedure using those data.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Even if a model-fitting procedure has been used, *R*2 may still be negative, for example when linear regression is conducted without including an intercept, or when a non-linear function is used to fit the data.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In cases where negative values arise, the mean of the data provides a better fit to the outcomes than do the fitted function values, according to this particular criterion.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The coefficient of determination can be more intuitively informative than MAE, MAPE, MSE, and RMSE in regression analysis evaluation, as the former can be expressed as a percentage, whereas the latter measures have arbitrary ranges.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] It also proved more robust for poor fits compared to SMAPE on certain test datasets.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] When evaluating the goodness-of-fit of simulated (*Y*pred) versus measured (*Y*obs) values, it is not appropriate to base this on the *R*2 of the linear regression (i.e., *Y*obs=*m*·*Y*pred + b).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The *R*2 quantifies the degree of any linear correlation between *Y*obs and *Y*pred, while for the goodness-of-fit evaluation only one specific linear correlation should be taken into consideration: *Y*obs=1·*Y*pred + 0 (i.e., the 1:1 line).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In the best case, the modeled values exactly match the observed values, which results in $SS_{\text{res}}=0$ and *R*2=1.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] A baseline model, which always predicts *y*, will have *R*2=0.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] A larger value of *R*2 implies a more successful regression model.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] This implies that 49% of the variability of the dependent variable in the data set has been accounted for, and the remaining 51% of the variability is still unaccounted for.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] See Partitioning in the general OLS model for a derivation of this result for one case where the relation holds.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] where *n* is the number of observations (cases) on the variables.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In this form *R*2 is expressed as the ratio of the explained variance (variance of the model's predictions, which is *SS*reg / *n*) to the total variance (sample variance of the dependent variable, which is *SS*tot / *n*).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] This partition of the sum of squares holds for instance when the model values *ƒ**i* have been obtained by linear regression.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] where the *q**i* are arbitrary values that may or may not depend on *i* or on other free parameters (the common choice *q**i* = *x**i* is just one special case), and the coefficient estimates ${\widehat {\alpha }}$ and ${\widehat {\beta }}$ are obtained by minimizing the residual sum of squares.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] This set of conditions is an important one and it has a number of implications for the properties of the fitted residuals and the modelled values.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In linear least squares multiple regression (with fitted intercept and slope), *R*2 equals $\rho ^{2}(y,f)$ the square of the Pearson correlation coefficient between the observed y and modeled (predicted) f data values of the dependent variable.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In a linear least squares regression with a single explanator (with fitted intercept and slope), this is also equal to $\rho ^{2}(y,x)$ the squared Pearson correlation coefficient between the dependent variable y and explanatory variable x .
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] where the covariance between two coefficient estimates, as well as their standard deviations, are obtained from the covariance matrix of the coefficient estimates, $(X^{T}X)^{-1}$ .
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Under more general modeling conditions, where the predicted values might be generated from a model different from linear least squares regression, an *R*2 value can be calculated as the square of the correlation coefficient between the original y and modeled f data values.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In this case, the value is not directly a measure of how good the modeled values are, but rather a measure of how good a predictor might be constructed from the modeled values (by creating a revised predictor of the form *α* + *βƒ**i*).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] According to Everitt, this usage is specifically the definition of the term "coefficient of determination": the square of the correlation between two (general) variables.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Values of *R*2 outside the range 0 to 1 occur when the model fits the data worse than the worst possible least-squares predictor (equivalent to a horizontal hyperplane at a height equal to the mean of the observed data).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] This occurs when a wrong model was chosen, or nonsensical constraints were applied by mistake.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] If equation 1 of Kvålseth is used (this is the equation used most often), *R*2 can be less than zero.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] If equation 2 of Kvålseth is used, *R*2 can be greater than one.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In all instances where *R*2 is used, the predictors are calculated by ordinary least-squares regression: that is, by minimizing *SS*res.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In this case, *R*2 increases as the number of variables in the model is increased (*R*2 is monotone increasing with the number of variables included—it will never decrease).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] This illustrates a drawback to one possible use of *R*2, where one might keep adding variables (kitchen sink regression) to increase the *R*2 value.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] This leads to the alternative approach of looking at the adjusted *R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The explanation of this statistic is almost the same as *R*2 but it penalizes the statistic as extra variables are included in the model.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] For cases other than fitting by ordinary least squares, the *R*2 statistic can be calculated as above and may still be a useful measure.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] If fitting is by weighted least squares or generalized least squares, alternative versions of *R*2 can be calculated appropriate to those statistical frameworks, while the "raw" *R*2 may still be useful if it is more easily interpreted.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Values for *R*2 can be calculated for any type of predictive model, which need not have a statistical basis.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] where, for the *i*th case, ${Y_{i}}$ is the response variable, $X_{i,1},\dots ,X_{i,p}$ are *p* regressors, and $\varepsilon _{i}$ is a mean zero error term.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The quantities $\beta _{0},\dots ,\beta _{p}$ are unknown coefficients, whose values are estimated by least squares.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The coefficient of determination *R*2 is a measure of the global fit of the model.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Specifically, *R*2 is an element of [0, 1] and represents the proportion of variability in *Y**i* that may be attributed to some linear combination of the regressors (explanatory variables) in *X*.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] A caution that applies to *R*2, as to other statistical descriptions of correlation and association is that "correlation does not imply causation".
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] For example, the practice of carrying matches (or a lighter) is correlated with incidence of lung cancer, but carrying matches does not cause cancer (in the standard sense of "cause").
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In case of a single regressor, fitted by least squares, *R*2 is the square of the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient relating the regressor and the response variable.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] More generally, *R*2 is the square of the correlation between the constructed predictor and the response variable.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] With more than one regressor, the *R*2 can be referred to as the coefficient of multiple determination.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In least squares regression using typical data, *R*2 is at least weakly increasing with an increase in number of regressors in the model.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Because increases in the number of regressors increase the value of *R*2, *R*2 alone cannot be used as a meaningful comparison of models with very different numbers of independent variables.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] For a meaningful comparison between two models, an F-test can be performed on the residual sum of squares , similar to the F-tests in Granger causality, though this is not always appropriate.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] As a reminder of this, some authors denote *R*2 by *R**q*2, where *q* is the number of columns in *X* (the number of explanators including the constant).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] where *Xi* is a row vector of values of explanatory variables for case *i* and *b* is a column vector of coefficients of the respective elements of *Xi*.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Given the previous conclusion and noting that $SS_{tot}$ depends only on *y*, the non-decreasing property of *R*2 follows directly from the definition above.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The intuitive reason that using an additional explanatory variable cannot lower the *R*2 is this: Minimizing $SS_{\text{res}}$ is equivalent to maximizing *R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] When the extra variable is included, the data always have the option of giving it an estimated coefficient of zero, leaving the predicted values and the *R*2 unchanged.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The only way that the optimization problem will give a non-zero coefficient is if doing so improves the *R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The above gives an analytical explanation of the inflation of *R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Next, an example based on ordinary least square from a geometric perspective is shown below.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] This equation describes the ordinary least squares regression model with one regressor.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The prediction is shown as the red vector in the figure on the right.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Geometrically, it is the projection of true value onto a model space in $\mathbb {R}$ (without intercept).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] This equation corresponds to the ordinary least squares regression model with two regressors.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The prediction is shown as the blue vector in the figure on the right.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Geometrically, it is the projection of true value onto a larger model space in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ (without intercept).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Noticeably, the values of $\beta _{0}$ and $\beta _{0}$ are not the same as in the equation for smaller model space as long as $X_{1}$ and $X_{2}$ are not zero vectors.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Therefore, the equations are expected to yield different predictions (i.e., the blue vector is expected to be different from the red vector).
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The least squares regression criterion ensures that the residual is minimized.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In the figure, the blue line representing the residual is orthogonal to the model space in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , giving the minimal distance from the space.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The smaller model space is a subspace of the larger one, and thereby the residual of the smaller model is guaranteed to be larger.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Comparing the red and blue lines in the figure, the blue line is orthogonal to the space, and any other line would be larger than the blue one.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Considering the calculation for *R*2, a smaller value of $SS_{tot}$ will lead to a larger value of *R*2, meaning that adding regressors will result in inflation of *R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The use of an adjusted *R*2 (one common notation is ${\bar {R}}^{2}$ , pronounced "R bar squared"; another is $R_{\text{a}}^{2}$ or $R_{\text{adj}}^{2}$ ) is an attempt to account for the phenomenon of the *R*2 automatically increasing when extra explanatory variables are added to the model.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] There are many different ways of adjusting.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] By far the most used one, to the point that it is typically just referred to as adjusted *R*, is the correction proposed by Mordecai Ezekiel.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] where *p* is the total number of explanatory variables in the model (excluding the intercept), and *n* is the sample size.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The adjusted *R*2 can be negative, and its value will always be less than or equal to that of *R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Unlike *R*2, the adjusted *R*2 increases only when the increase in *R*2 (due to the inclusion of a new explanatory variable) is more than one would expect to see by chance.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The adjusted *R*2 can be interpreted as an instance of the bias-variance tradeoff.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] When we consider the performance of a model, a lower error represents a better performance.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] When the model becomes more complex, the variance will increase whereas the square of bias will decrease, and these two metrics add up to be the total error.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Combining these two trends, the bias-variance tradeoff describes a relationship between the performance of the model and its complexity, which is shown as a u-shape curve on the right.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] For the adjusted *R*2 specifically, the model complexity (i.e. number of parameters) affects the *R*2 and the term / frac and thereby captures their attributes in the overall performance of the model.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] On the other hand, the term/frac term is reversely affected by the model complexity.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The term/frac will increase when adding regressors (i.e., increased model complexity) and lead to worse performance.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Based on bias-variance tradeoff, a higher model complexity (beyond the optimal line) leads to increasing errors and a worse performance.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Considering the calculation of *R*2, more parameters will increase the *R*2 and lead to an increase in *R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Nevertheless, adding more parameters will increase the term/frac and thus decrease *R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] These two trends construct a reverse u-shape relationship between model complexity and *R*2, which is in consistent with the u-shape trend of model complexity versus overall performance.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Unlike *R*2, which will always increase when model complexity increases, *R*2 will increase only when the bias eliminated by the added regressor is greater than the variance introduced simultaneously.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Using *R*2 instead of *R*2 could thereby prevent overfitting.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Following the same logic, adjusted *R*2 can be interpreted as a less biased estimator of the population *R*2, whereas the observed sample *R*2 is a positively biased estimate of the population value.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Adjusted *R*2 is more appropriate when evaluating model fit (the variance in the dependent variable accounted for by the independent variables) and in comparing alternative models in the feature selection stage of model building.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Despite using unbiased estimators for the population variances of the error and the dependent variable, adjusted *R*2 is not an unbiased estimator of the population *R*2, which results by using the population variances of the errors and the dependent variable instead of estimating them.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Pratt derived the minimum-variance unbiased estimator for the population *R*2, which is known as Olkin–Pratt estimator.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Comparisons of different approaches for adjusting *R*2 concluded that in most situations either an approximate version of the Olkin–Pratt estimator or the exact Olkin–Pratt estimator should be preferred over (Ezekiel) adjusted *R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The coefficient of partial determination can be defined as the proportion of variation that cannot be explained in a reduced model, but can be explained by the predictors specified in a full model.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] This coefficient is used to provide insight into whether or not one or more additional predictors may be useful in a more fully specified regression model.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The calculation for the partial *R*2 is relatively straightforward after estimating two models and generating the ANOVA tables for them.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] As explained above, model selection heuristics such as the adjusted *R*2 criterion and the F-test examine whether the total *R*2 sufficiently increases to determine if a new regressor should be added to the model.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] If a regressor is added to the model that is highly correlated with other regressors which have already been included, then the total *R*2 will hardly increase, even if the new regressor is of relevance.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] As a result, the above-mentioned heuristics will ignore relevant regressors when cross-correlations are high.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Alternatively, one can decompose a generalized version of *R*2 to quantify the relevance of deviating from a hypothesis.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] As Hoornweg (2018) shows, several shrinkage estimators – such as Bayesian linear regression, ridge regression, and the (adaptive) lasso – make use of this decomposition of *R*2 when they gradually shrink parameters from the unrestricted OLS solutions towards the hypothesized values.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] It is assumed that the matrix *X* is standardized with Z-scores and that the column vector y is centered to have a mean of zero.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Let the column vector $\beta _{0}$ refer to the hypothesized regression parameters and let the column vector b denote the estimated parameters.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] An *R*2 of 75% means that the in-sample accuracy improves by 75% if the data-optimized *b* solutions are used instead of the hypothesized $\beta _{0}$ values.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In the special case that $\beta _{0}$ is a vector of zeros, we obtain the traditional *R*2 again.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The individual effect on *R*2 of deviating from a hypothesis can be computed with $R^{\otimes }$ ('R-outer').
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The diagonal elements of $R^{\otimes }$ exactly add up to *R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] If regressors are uncorrelated and $\beta _{0}$ is a vector of zeros, then the $j^{\text{th}}$ diagonal element of $R^{\otimes }$ simply corresponds to the *r*2 value between $x_{j}$ and y .
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] When regressors $x_{i}$ and $x_{j}$ are correlated, $R_{ii}^{\otimes }$ might increase at the cost of a decrease in $R_{jj}^{\otimes }$ .
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] As a result, the diagonal elements of $R^{\otimes }$ may be smaller than 0 and, in more exceptional cases, larger than 1.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] To deal with such uncertainties, several shrinkage estimators implicitly take a weighted average of the diagonal elements of $R^{\otimes }$ to quantify the relevance of deviating from a hypothesized value.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] In the case of logistic regression, usually fit by maximum likelihood, there are several choices of pseudo-*R*2.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] where ${\mathcal {L}}(0)$ is the likelihood of the model with only the intercept, ${{\mathcal {L}}({\widehat {\theta }})}$ is the likelihood of the estimated model (i.e., the model with a given set of parameter estimates) and *n* is the sample size.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] where *D* is the test statistic of the likelihood ratio test.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] However, in the case of a logistic model, where ${\mathcal {L}}({\widehat {\theta }})$ cannot be greater than 1, *R*2 is between 0 and $R_{\max }^{2}=1-({\mathcal {L}}(0))^{2/n}$ : thus, Nagelkerke suggested the possibility to define a scaled *R*2 as *R*2/*R*2max.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Occasionally, residual statistics are used for indicating goodness of fit.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Similarly, the reduced chi-square is calculated as the SSR divided by the degrees of freedom.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Both *R*2 and the norm of residuals have their relative merits.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] For least squares analysis *R*2 varies between 0 and 1, with larger numbers indicating better fits and 1 representing a perfect fit.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The norm of residuals varies from 0 to infinity with smaller numbers indicating better fits and zero indicating a perfect fit.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] One advantage and disadvantage of *R*2 is the $SS_{\text{tot}}$ term acts to normalize the value.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] If the *yi* values are all multiplied by a constant, the norm of residuals will also change by that constant but *R*2 will stay the same.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] Another single-parameter indicator of fit is the RMSE of the residuals, or standard deviation of the residuals.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] This would have a value of 0.135 for the above example given that the fit was linear with an unforced intercept.
[src:linear-regression/coefficient-of-determination] The creation of the coefficient of determination has been attributed to the geneticist Sewall Wright and was first published in 1921.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] In statistics and in particular in regression analysis, a **design matrix**, also known as **model matrix** or **regressor matrix** and often denoted by **X**, is a matrix of values of explanatory variables of a set of objects.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] Each row represents an individual object, with the successive columns corresponding to the variables and their specific values for that object.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The design matrix is used in certain statistical models, e.g., the general linear model.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] It can contain indicator variables (ones and zeros) that indicate group membership in an ANOVA, or it can contain values of continuous variables.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The design matrix contains data on the independent variables (also called explanatory variables), in a statistical model that is intended to explain observed data on a response variable (often called a dependent variable).
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The theory relating to such models uses the design matrix as input to some linear algebra : see for example linear regression.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] A notable feature of the concept of a design matrix is that it is able to represent a number of different experimental designs and statistical models, e.g., ANOVA, ANCOVA, and linear regression.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The design matrix is defined to be a matrix X such that $X_{ij}$ (the *j*th column of the *i*th row of X ) represents the value of the *j*th variable associated with the *i*th object.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] where *X* is the design matrix, $\beta$ is a vector of the model's coefficients (one for each variable), e is a vector of random errors with mean zero, and *y* is the vector of predicted outputs for each object.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The design matrix has dimension *n*-by-*p*, where *n* is the number of samples observed, and *p* is the number of variables (features) measured in all samples.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] In this representation different rows typically represent different repetitions of an experiment, while columns represent different types of data (say, the results from particular probes).
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] For example, suppose an experiment is run where 10 people are pulled off the street and asked 4 questions.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The data matrix *M* would be a 10×4 matrix (meaning 10 rows and 4 columns).
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The datum in row *i* and column *j* of this matrix would be the answer of the *i* th person to the *j* th question.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The design matrix for an arithmetic mean is a column vector of ones.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] This section gives an example of simple linear regression—that is, regression with only a single explanatory variable—with seven observations.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] where $\beta _{0}$ is the *y*-intercept and $\beta _{1}$ is the slope of the regression line.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] where the first column of 1s in the design matrix allows estimation of the *y*-intercept while the second column contains the *x*-values associated with the corresponding *y*-values.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The matrix whose columns are 1's and *x'*s in this example is the design matrix.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] This section contains an example of multiple regression with two covariates (explanatory variables): *w* and *x*.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] Again suppose that the data consist of seven observations, and that for each observed value to be predicted ( $y_{i}$ ), values *w**i* and *x**i* of the two covariates are also observed.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] Here the 7×3 matrix on the right side is the design matrix.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] This section contains an example with a one-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) with three groups and seven observations.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The given data set has the first three observations belonging to the first group, the following two observations belonging to the second group and the final two observations belonging to the third group.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] In this model $\mu _{i}$ represents the mean of the i th group.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] The ANOVA model could be equivalently written as each group parameter $\tau _{i}$ being an offset from some overall reference.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] Typically this reference point is taken to be one of the groups under consideration.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] This makes sense in the context of comparing multiple treatment groups to a control group and the control group is considered the "reference".
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] In this example, group 1 was chosen to be the reference group.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] with the constraint that $\tau _{1}$ is zero.
[src:linear-regression/design-matrix] In this model $\mu$ is the mean of the reference group and $\tau _{i}$ is the difference from group i to the reference group. $\tau _{1}$ is not included in the matrix because its difference from the reference group (itself) is necessarily zero.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] In statistics and optimization, **errors** and **residuals** are two closely related and easily confused measures of the deviation of an observed value of an element of a statistical sample from its "true value" (not necessarily observable).
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The **error** of an observation is the deviation of the observed value from the true value of a quantity of interest (for example, a population mean).
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The **residual** is the difference between the observed value and the *estimated* value of the quantity of interest (for example, a sample mean).
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The distinction is most important in regression analysis, where the concepts are sometimes called the **regression errors** and **regression residuals** and where they lead to the concept of studentized residuals.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] In econometrics, "errors" are also called **disturbances**.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] Suppose there is a series of observations from a univariate distribution and we want to estimate the mean of that distribution (the so-called location model).
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] In this case, the errors are the deviations of the observations from the population mean, while the residuals are the deviations of the observations from the sample mean.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] A **statistical error** (or **disturbance**) is the amount by which an observation differs from its expected value, the latter being based on the whole population from which the statistical unit was chosen randomly.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] For example, if the mean height in a population of 21-year-old men is 1.75 meters, and one randomly chosen man is 1.80 meters tall, then the "error" is 0.05 meters; if the randomly chosen man is 1.70 meters tall, then the "error" is −0.05 meters.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The expected value, being the mean of the entire population, is typically unobservable, and hence the statistical error cannot be observed either.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] A **residual** (or fitting deviation), on the other hand, is an observable *estimate* of the unobservable statistical error.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] Consider the previous example with men's heights and suppose we have a random sample of *n* people.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The *sample mean* could serve as a good estimator of the *population* mean.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] Note that, because of the definition of the sample mean, the sum of the residuals within a random sample is necessarily zero, and thus the residuals are necessarily *not independent*.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The statistical errors, on the other hand, are independent, and their sum within the random sample is almost surely not zero.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] One can standardize statistical errors (especially of a normal distribution) in a z-score (or "standard score"), and standardize residuals in a *t*-statistic, or more generally studentized residuals.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] However, this quantity is not observable as the population mean is unknown.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The sum of squares of the **residuals**, on the other hand, is observable.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] This difference between *n* and *n* − 1 degrees of freedom results in Bessel's correction for the estimation of sample variance of a population with unknown mean and unknown variance.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] No correction is necessary if the population mean is known.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] It is remarkable that the sum of squares of the residuals and the sample mean can be shown to be independent of each other, using, e.g.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The probability distributions of the numerator and the denominator separately depend on the value of the unobservable population standard deviation *σ*, but *σ* appears in both the numerator and the denominator and cancels.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] That is fortunate because it means that even though we do not know *σ*, we know the probability distribution of this quotient: it has a Student's t-distribution with *n* − 1 degrees of freedom.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] We can therefore use this quotient to find a confidence interval for *μ*.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] In regression analysis, the distinction between *errors* and *residuals* is subtle and important, and leads to the concept of studentized residuals.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] Given an unobservable function that relates the independent variable to the dependent variable – say, a line – the deviations of the dependent variable observations from this function are the unobservable errors.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] If one runs a regression on some data, then the deviations of the dependent variable observations from the *fitted* function are the residuals.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] If the linear model is applicable, a scatterplot of residuals plotted against the independent variable should be random about zero with no trend to the residuals.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] If the data exhibit a trend, the regression model is likely incorrect; for example, the true function may be a quadratic or higher order polynomial.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] If they are random, or have no trend, but "fan out" - they exhibit a phenomenon called heteroscedasticity.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] If all of the residuals are equal, or do not fan out, they exhibit homoscedasticity.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] However, a terminological difference arises in the expression mean squared error (MSE).
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The mean squared error of a regression is a number computed from the sum of squares of the computed *residuals*, and not of the unobservable *errors*.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] If that sum of squares is divided by *n*, the number of observations, the result is the mean of the squared residuals.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] This forms an unbiased estimate of the variance of the unobserved errors, and is called the mean squared error.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] One can then also calculate the mean square of the model by dividing the sum of squares of the model minus the degrees of freedom, which is just the number of parameters.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] Then the F value can be calculated by dividing the mean square of the model by the mean square of the error, and we can then determine significance (which is why you want the mean squares to begin with.).
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] However, because of the behavior of the process of regression, the *distributions* of residuals at different data points (of the input variable) may vary *even if* the errors themselves are identically distributed.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] Concretely, in a linear regression where the errors are identically distributed, the variability of residuals of inputs in the middle of the domain will be *higher* than the variability of residuals at the ends of the domain: linear regressions fit endpoints better than the middle.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] This is also reflected in the influence functions of various data points on the regression coefficients: endpoints have more influence.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] Thus to compare residuals at different inputs, one needs to adjust the residuals by the expected variability of *residuals,* which is called studentizing.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] This is particularly important in the case of detecting outliers, where the case in question is somehow different from the others in a dataset.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] For example, a large residual may be expected in the middle of the domain, but considered an outlier at the end of the domain.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The use of the term "error" as discussed in the sections above is in the sense of a deviation of a value from a hypothetical unobserved value.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The *mean squared error* (MSE) refers to the amount by which the values predicted by an estimator differ from the quantities being estimated (typically outside the sample from which the model was estimated).
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The *root mean square error* (RMSE) is the square root of MSE.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The *sum of squares of errors* (SSE) is the MSE multiplied by the sample size.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] Likewise, the *sum of absolute errors* (SAE) is the sum of the absolute values of the residuals, which is minimized in the least absolute deviations approach to regression.
[src:linear-regression/errors-and-residuals] The *mean residual* (MR) is always zero for least-squares estimators.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The errors do not need to be normal, nor do they need to be independent and identically distributed (only uncorrelated with mean zero and homoscedastic with finite variance).
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The requirement that the estimator be unbiased cannot be dropped, since biased estimators exist with lower variance.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] See, for example, the James–Stein estimator (which also drops linearity), ridge regression, or simply any degenerate estimator.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The theorem was named after Carl Friedrich Gauss and Andrey Markov, although Gauss' work significantly predates Markov's.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] But while Gauss derived the result under the assumption of independence and normality, Markov reduced the assumptions to the form stated above.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] A further generalization to non-spherical errors was given by Alexander Aitken.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Suppose we are given two random variables $X,Y$ and that we want to find the best linear estimator of Y given X , using the best linear estimator ${\hat {Y}}=\alpha X+\mu ,$ where the parameters $\alpha$ and $\mu$ are both real numbers.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Such an estimator ${\hat {Y}}$ would have the same mean and standard deviation as Y , that is, $\mu _{\hat {Y}}=\mu _{Y},\sigma _{\hat {Y}}=\sigma _{Y}$ .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Therefore, if the vector X has respective mean and standard deviation $\mu _{x},\sigma _{x}$ , the best linear estimator would be ${\hat {Y}}=\sigma _{y}{\frac {(X-\mu _{x})}{\sigma _{x}}}+\mu _{y},$ since ${\hat {Y}}$ has the same mean and standard deviation as Y .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The random variables $\varepsilon _{i}$ are called the "disturbance", "noise" or simply "error" (will be contrasted with "residual" later in the article; see errors and residuals in statistics).
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Note that to include a constant in the model above, one can choose to introduce the constant as a variable $\beta _{K+1}$ with a newly introduced last column of X being unity i.e., $X_{i(K+1)}=1$ for all i .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Now, let ${\textstyle \sum _{j=1}^{K}\lambda _{j}\beta _{j}}$ be some linear combination of the coefficients.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] This is equivalent to the condition that $\operatorname {Var} ({\tilde {\beta }})-\operatorname {Var} ({\hat {\beta }})$ is a positive semi-definite matrix for every other linear unbiased estimator ${\widetilde {\beta }}$ .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The theorem now states that the OLS estimator is a best linear unbiased estimator (BLUE).
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The main idea of the proof is that the least-squares estimator is uncorrelated with every linear unbiased estimator of zero, i.e., with every linear combination $a_{1}y_{1}+\cdots +a_{n}y_{n}$ whose coefficients do not depend upon the unobservable $\beta$ but whose expected value is always zero.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Proof that the OLS indeed *minimizes* the sum of squares of residuals may proceed as follows with a calculation of the Hessian matrix and showing that it is positive definite.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Finally, as eigenvector $\mathbf {k}$ was arbitrary, it means all eigenvalues of ${\mathcal {H}}$ are positive, therefore ${\mathcal {H}}$ is positive definite.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Thus, ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}=\left(X^{\operatorname {T} }X\right)^{-1}X^{\operatorname {T} }Y$ is indeed a global minimum.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Or, just see that for all vectors $\mathbf {v} ,\mathbf {v} ^{\operatorname {T} }X^{\operatorname {T} }X\mathbf {v} =\|\mathbf {X} \mathbf {v} \|^{2}\geq 0$ .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] So the Hessian is positive definite if full rank.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Let ${\tilde {\beta }}=Cy$ be another linear estimator of $\beta$ with $C=(X^{\operatorname {T} }X)^{-1}X^{\operatorname {T} }+D$ where D is a $K\times n$ non-zero matrix.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] As we're restricting to *unbiased* estimators, minimum mean squared error implies minimum variance.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The goal is therefore to show that such an estimator has a variance no smaller than that of ${\widehat {\beta }},$ the OLS estimator.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Therefore, since $\beta$ is **un**observable, ${\tilde {\beta }}$ is unbiased if and only if $DX=0$ .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Since $DD^{\operatorname {T} }$ is a positive semidefinite matrix, $\operatorname {Var} \left({\tilde {\beta }}\right)$ exceeds $\operatorname {Var} \left({\widehat {\beta }}\right)$ by a positive semidefinite matrix.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] To see this, let $\ell ^{\operatorname {T} }{\tilde {\beta }}$ another linear unbiased estimator of $\ell ^{\operatorname {T} }\beta$ .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Moreover, equality holds if and only if $D^{\operatorname {T} }\ell =0$ .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] This proves that the equality holds if and only if $\ell ^{\operatorname {T} }{\tilde {\beta }}=\ell ^{\operatorname {T} }{\widehat {\beta }}$ which gives the uniqueness of the OLS estimator as a BLUE.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The generalized least squares (GLS), developed by Aitken, extends the Gauss–Markov theorem to the case where the error vector has a non-scalar covariance matrix.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] In most treatments of OLS, the regressors (parameters of interest) in the design matrix $\mathbf {X}$ are assumed to be fixed in repeated samples.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] This assumption is considered inappropriate for a predominantly nonexperimental science like econometrics.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Instead, the assumptions of the Gauss–Markov theorem are stated conditional on $\mathbf {X}$ .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The dependent variable is assumed to be a linear function of the variables specified in the model.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The specification must be linear in its parameters.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] This does not mean that there must be a linear relationship between the independent and dependent variables.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The independent variables can take non-linear forms as long as the parameters are linear.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The equation $y=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x^{2},$ qualifies as linear while $y=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}^{2}x$ can be transformed to be linear by replacing $\beta _{1}^{2}$ by another parameter, say $\gamma$ .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] An equation with a parameter dependent on an independent variable does not qualify as linear, for example $y=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}(x)\cdot x$ , where $\beta _{1}(x)$ is a function of x .
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Data transformations are often used to convert an equation into a linear form.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] This assumption also covers specification issues: assuming that the proper functional form has been selected and there are no omitted variables.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] One should be aware, however, that the parameters that minimize the residuals of the transformed equation do not necessarily minimize the residuals of the original equation.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Geometrically, this assumption implies that $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ and $\varepsilon _{i}$ are orthogonal to each other, so that their inner product (i.e., their cross moment) is zero.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] This assumption is violated if the explanatory variables are measured with error, or are endogenous.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Endogeneity can be the result of simultaneity, where causality flows back and forth between both the dependent and independent variable.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Instrumental variable techniques are commonly used to address this problem.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The sample data matrix $\mathbf {X}$ must have full column rank.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Otherwise $\mathbf {X} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {X}$ is not invertible and the OLS estimator cannot be computed.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] A violation of this assumption is perfect multicollinearity, i.e. some explanatory variables are linearly dependent.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] One scenario in which this will occur is called "dummy variable trap," when a base dummy variable is not omitted resulting in perfect correlation between the dummy variables and the constant term.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Multicollinearity (as long as it is not "perfect") can be present resulting in a less efficient, but still unbiased estimate.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The estimates will be less precise and highly sensitive to particular sets of data.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Multicollinearity can be detected from condition number or the variance inflation factor, among other tests.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] The outer product of the error vector must be spherical.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] This implies the error term has uniform variance (homoscedasticity) and no serial correlation.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] If this assumption is violated, OLS is still unbiased, but inefficient.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Heteroskedasticity occurs when the amount of error is correlated with an independent variable.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] For example, in a regression on food expenditure and income, the error is correlated with income.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Low income people generally spend a similar amount on food, while high income people may spend a very large amount or as little as low income people spend.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Heteroskedastic can also be caused by changes in measurement practices.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] For example, as statistical offices improve their data, measurement error decreases, so the error term declines over time.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] This assumption is violated when there is autocorrelation.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Autocorrelation can be visualized on a data plot when a given observation is more likely to lie above a fitted line if adjacent observations also lie above the fitted regression line.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Autocorrelation is common in time series data where a data series may experience "inertia." If a dependent variable takes a while to fully absorb a shock.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Spatial autocorrelation can also occur geographic areas are likely to have similar errors.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] Autocorrelation may be the result of misspecification such as choosing the wrong functional form.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] In these cases, correcting the specification is one possible way to deal with autocorrelation.
[src:linear-regression/gauss-markov-theorem] When the spherical errors assumption may be violated, the generalized least squares estimator can be shown to be BLUE.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In statistics, **linear regression** is a model that estimates the relationship between a scalar response (dependent variable) and one or more explanatory variables (**regressor** or independent variable).
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] A model with exactly one explanatory variable is a *simple linear regression*; a model with two or more explanatory variables is a **multiple linear regression**.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This term is distinct from multivariate linear regression, which predicts multiple correlated dependent variables rather than a single dependent variable.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In linear regression, the relationships are modeled using linear predictor functions whose unknown model parameters are estimated from the data.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Most commonly, the conditional mean of the response given the values of the explanatory variables (or predictors) is assumed to be an affine function of those values; less commonly, the conditional median or some other quantile is used.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Like all forms of regression analysis, linear regression focuses on the conditional probability distribution of the response given the values of the predictors, rather than on the joint probability distribution of all of these variables, which is the domain of multivariate analysis.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Linear regression is also a type of machine learning algorithm, more specifically a supervised algorithm, that learns from the labelled datasets and maps the data points to the most optimized linear functions that can be used for prediction on new datasets.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Linear regression was the first type of regression analysis to be studied rigorously, and to be used extensively in practical applications.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This is because models which depend linearly on their unknown parameters are easier to fit than models which are non-linearly related to their parameters and because the statistical properties of the resulting estimators are easier to determine.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Linear regression has many practical uses.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Use of the Mean Squared Error (MSE) as the cost on a dataset that has many large outliers, can result in a model that fits the outliers more than the true data due to the higher importance assigned by MSE to large errors.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] So, cost functions that are robust to outliers should be used if the dataset has many large outliers.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Conversely, the least squares approach can be used to fit models that are not linear models.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Thus, although the terms "least squares" and "linear model" are closely linked, they are not synonymous.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Given a data set $\{y_{i},\,x_{i1},\ldots ,x_{ip}\}_{i=1}^{n}$ of *n* statistical units, a linear regression model assumes that the relationship between the dependent variable *y* and the vector of regressors **x** is linear.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This relationship is modeled through a *disturbance term* or *error variable* *ε*—an unobserved random variable that adds extra "noise" to the linear relationship between the dependent variable and regressors.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Fitting a linear model to a given data set usually requires estimating the regression coefficients ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ such that the error term ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}=\mathbf {y} -\mathbf {X} {\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ is minimized.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] For example, it is common to use the sum of squared errors $\|{\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}\|_{2}^{2}$ as a measure of ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}$ for minimization.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Consider a situation where a small ball is being tossed up in the air and then we measure its heights of ascent *hi* at various moments in time *ti*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] where *β*1 determines the initial velocity of the ball, *β*2 is proportional to the standard gravity, and *ε**i* is due to measurement errors.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Linear regression can be used to estimate the values of *β*1 and *β*2 from the measured data.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Numerous extensions have been developed that allow each of these assumptions to be relaxed (reduced to a weaker form), and in some cases eliminated entirely.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Generally these extensions require more data or modelling assumptions to produce an equally precise model.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] A fitted linear regression model can be used to identify the relationship between a single predictor variable *x**j* and the response variable *y* when all the other predictor variables in the model are "held fixed".
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Specifically, the interpretation of *β**j* is the expected change in *y* for a one-unit change in *x**j* when the other covariates are held fixed—that is, the expected value of the partial derivative of *y* with respect to *x**j*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This is sometimes called the *unique effect* of *x**j* on *y*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In contrast, the *marginal effect* of *x**j* on *y* can be assessed using a correlation coefficient or simple linear regression model relating only *x**j* to *y*; this effect is the total derivative of *y* with respect to *x**j*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] It is possible that the unique effect be nearly zero even when the marginal effect is large.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This may imply that some other covariate captures all the information in *x**j*, so that once that variable is in the model, there is no contribution of *x**j* to the variation in *y*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Conversely, the unique effect of *x**j* can be large while its marginal effect is nearly zero.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This would happen if the other covariates explained a great deal of the variation of *y*, but they mainly explain variation in a way that is complementary to what is captured by *x**j*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In this case, including the other variables in the model reduces the part of the variability of *y* that is unrelated to *x**j*, thereby strengthening the apparent relationship with *x**j*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The meaning of the expression "held fixed" may depend on how the values of the predictor variables arise.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] If the experimenter directly sets the values of the predictor variables according to a study design, the comparisons of interest may literally correspond to comparisons among units whose predictor variables have been "held fixed" by the experimenter.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Alternatively, the expression "held fixed" can refer to a selection that takes place in the context of data analysis.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In this case, we "hold a variable fixed" by restricting our attention to the subsets of the data that happen to have a common value for the given predictor variable.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This is the only interpretation of "held fixed" that can be used in an observational study.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The notion of a "unique effect" is appealing when studying a complex system where multiple interrelated components influence the response variable.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In some cases, it can literally be interpreted as the causal effect of an intervention that is linked to the value of a predictor variable.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] However, it has been argued that in many cases multiple regression analysis fails to clarify the relationships between the predictor variables and the response variable when the predictors are correlated with each other and are not assigned following a study design.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Numerous extensions of linear regression have been developed, which allow some or all of the assumptions underlying the basic model to be relaxed.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The simplest case of a single scalar predictor variable *x* and a single scalar response variable *y* is known as *simple linear regression*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The extension to multiple and/or vector-valued predictor variables (denoted with a capital *X*) is known as **multiple linear regression**, also known as **multivariable linear regression** (not to be confused with *multivariate linear regression*).
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Multiple linear regression is a generalization of simple linear regression to the case of more than one independent variable, and a special case of general linear models, restricted to one dependent variable.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] for each observation ${\textstyle i=1,\ldots ,n}$ .
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In the formula above we consider *n* observations of one dependent variable and *p* independent variables.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Thus, *Y**i* is the *i*th observation of the dependent variable, *X**ij* is *i*th observation of the *j*th independent variable, *j* = 1, 2, ..., *p*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The values *β**j* represent parameters to be estimated, and *ε**i* is the *i*th independent identically distributed normal error.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] for all observations indexed as *i* = 1, ... , *n* and for all dependent variables indexed as *j* = 1, ... , *m*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Nearly all real-world regression models involve multiple predictors, and basic descriptions of linear regression are often phrased in terms of the multiple regression model.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Note, however, that in these cases the response variable *y* is still a scalar.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Another term, *multivariate linear regression*, refers to cases where *y* is a vector, i.e., the same as *general linear regression*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The general linear model considers the situation when the response variable is not a scalar (for each observation) but a vector, **y***i*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Conditional linearity of $E(\mathbf {y} \mid \mathbf {x} _{i})=\mathbf {x} _{i}^{\mathsf {T}}B$ is still assumed, with a matrix *B* replacing the vector ***β*** of the classical linear regression model.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Multivariate analogues of ordinary least squares (OLS) and generalized least squares (GLS) have been developed.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] "General linear models" are also called "multivariate linear models".
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] These are not the same as multivariable linear models (also called "multiple linear models").
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Various models have been created that allow for heteroscedasticity, i.e. the errors for different response variables may have different variances.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] For example, weighted least squares is a method for estimating linear regression models when the response variables may have different error variances, possibly with correlated errors.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] (See also Weighted linear least squares, and Generalized least squares.) Heteroscedasticity-consistent standard errors is an improved method for use with uncorrelated but potentially heteroscedastic errors.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The Generalized linear model (GLM) is a framework for modeling response variables that are bounded or discrete.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Generalized linear models allow for an arbitrary *link function*, *g*, that relates the mean of the response variable(s) to the predictors: $E(Y)=g^{-1}(XB)$ .
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The link function is often related to the distribution of the response, and in particular it typically has the effect of transforming between the $(-\infty ,\infty )$ range of the linear predictor and the range of the response variable.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Single index models allow some degree of nonlinearity in the relationship between *x* and *y*, while preserving the central role of the linear predictor *β*′*x* as in the classical linear regression model.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Under certain conditions, simply applying OLS to data from a single-index model will consistently estimate *β* up to a proportionality constant.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Hierarchical linear models (or *multilevel regression*) organizes the data into a hierarchy of regressions, for example where *A* is regressed on *B*, and *B* is regressed on *C*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] It is often used where the variables of interest have a natural hierarchical structure such as in educational statistics, where students are nested in classrooms, classrooms are nested in schools, and schools are nested in some administrative grouping, such as a school district.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The response variable might be a measure of student achievement such as a test score, and different covariates would be collected at the classroom, school, and school district levels.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Errors-in-variables models (or "measurement error models") extend the traditional linear regression model to allow the predictor variables *X* to be observed with error.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This error causes standard estimators of *β* to become biased.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Generally, the form of bias is an attenuation, meaning that the effects are biased toward zero.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] parameter $\beta _{j}$ of predictor variable $x_{j}$ represents the individual effect of $x_{j}$ .
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] It has an interpretation as the expected change in the response variable y when $x_{j}$ increases by one unit with other predictor variables held constant.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] When $x_{j}$ is strongly correlated with other predictor variables, it is improbable that $x_{j}$ can increase by one unit with other variables held constant.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In this case, the interpretation of $\beta _{j}$ becomes problematic as it is based on an improbable condition, and the effect of $x_{j}$ cannot be evaluated in isolation.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Because of the constraint on ${w_{j}}$ , $\xi (\mathbf {w} )$ is also referred to as a normalized group effect.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] A group effect $\xi (\mathbf {w} )$ has an interpretation as the expected change in y when variables in the group $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{q}$ change by the amount $w_{1},w_{2},\dots ,w_{q}$ , respectively, at the same time with other variables (not in the group) held constant.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] It generalizes the individual effect of a variable to a group of variables in that ( i ) if $q=1$ , then the group effect reduces to an individual effect, and ( $ii$ ) if $w_{i}=1$ and $w_{j}=0$ for $j\neq i$ , then the group effect also reduces to an individual effect.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] A group effect $\xi (\mathbf {w} )$ is said to be meaningful if the underlying simultaneous changes of the q variables $(x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{q})^{\intercal }$ is probable.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Group effects provide a means to study the collective impact of strongly correlated predictor variables in linear regression models.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Individual effects of such variables are not well-defined as their parameters do not have good interpretations.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Furthermore, when the sample size is not large, none of their parameters can be accurately estimated by the least squares regression due to the multicollinearity problem.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Nevertheless, there are meaningful group effects that have good interpretations and can be accurately estimated by the least squares regression.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] To illustrate this, suppose that $\{x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{q}\}$ is a group of strongly correlated variables in an APC arrangement and that they are not strongly correlated with predictor variables outside the group.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Let $y'$ be the centred y and $x_{j}'$ be the standardized $x_{j}$ .
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Parameters $\beta _{j}$ in the original model, including $\beta _{0}$ , are simple functions of $\beta _{j}'$ in the standardized model.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The standardization of variables does not change their correlations, so $\{x_{1}',x_{2}',\dots ,x_{q}'\}$ is a group of strongly correlated variables in an APC arrangement and they are not strongly correlated with other predictor variables in the standardized model.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] where ${\hat {\beta }}_{j}'$ is the least squares estimator of $\beta _{j}'$ .
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] which has an interpretation as the expected change in $y'$ when all $x_{j}'$ in the strongly correlated group increase by $(1/q)$ th of a unit at the same time with variables outside the group held constant.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] With strong positive correlations and in standardized units, variables in the group are approximately equal, so they are likely to increase at the same time and in similar amount.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Thus, the average group effect $\xi _{A}$ is a meaningful effect.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Not all group effects are meaningful or can be accurately estimated.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] For example, $\beta _{1}'$ is a special group effect with weights $w_{1}=1$ and $w_{j}=0$ for $j\neq 1$ , but it cannot be accurately estimated by ${\hat {\beta }}'_{1}$ .
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Effects with weight vectors far away from the centre are not meaningful as such weight vectors represent simultaneous changes of the variables that violate the strong positive correlations of the standardized variables in an APC arrangement.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] These effects also cannot be accurately estimated.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] A group effect of the original variables $\{x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{q}\}$ can be expressed as a constant times a group effect of the standardized variables $\{x_{1}',x_{2}',\dots ,x_{q}'\}$ .
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The former is meaningful when the latter is.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Thus meaningful group effects of the original variables can be found through meaningful group effects of the standardized variables.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In Dempster–Shafer theory, or a linear belief function in particular, a linear regression model may be represented as a partially swept matrix, which can be combined with similar matrices representing observations and other assumed normal distributions and state equations.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The combination of swept or unswept matrices provides an alternative method for estimating linear regression models.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] A large number of procedures have been developed for parameter estimation and inference in linear regression.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] These methods differ in computational simplicity of algorithms, presence of a closed-form solution, robustness with respect to heavy-tailed distributions, and theoretical assumptions needed to validate desirable statistical properties such as consistency and asymptotic efficiency.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Some of the more common estimation techniques for linear regression are summarized below.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] As the loss function is convex, the optimum solution lies at gradient zero.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Maximum likelihood estimation can be performed when the distribution of the error terms is known to belong to a certain parametric family *ƒθ* of probability distributions.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] When *f*θ is a normal distribution with zero mean and variance θ, the resulting estimate is identical to the OLS estimate.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] GLS estimates are maximum likelihood estimates when ε follows a multivariate normal distribution with a known covariance matrix.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] As shown below the same optimal parameter that minimizes $L(D,{\vec {\beta }})$ achieves maximum likelihood too.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Now, we need to look for a parameter that maximizes this likelihood function.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Since the logarithmic function is strictly increasing, instead of maximizing this function, we can also maximize its logarithm and find the optimal parameter that way.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In this way, the parameter that maximizes **$H(D,{\vec {\beta }})$** is the same as the one that minimizes **$L(D,{\vec {\beta }})$**.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This means that in linear regression, the result of the least squares method is the same as the result of the maximum likelihood estimation method.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Ridge regression and other forms of penalized estimation, such as Lasso regression, deliberately introduce bias into the estimation of *β* in order to reduce the variability of the estimate.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The resulting estimates generally have lower mean squared error than the OLS estimates, particularly when multicollinearity is present or when overfitting is a problem.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] They are generally used when the goal is to predict the value of the response variable *y* for values of the predictors *x* that have not yet been observed.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] These methods are not as commonly used when the goal is inference, since it is difficult to account for the bias.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Least absolute deviation (LAD) regression is a robust estimation technique in that it is less sensitive to the presence of outliers than OLS (but is less efficient than OLS when no outliers are present).
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] It is equivalent to maximum likelihood estimation under a Laplace distribution model for *ε*.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] If we assume that error terms are independent of the regressors, $\varepsilon _{i}\perp \mathbf {x} _{i}$ , then the optimal estimator is the 2-step MLE, where the first step is used to non-parametrically estimate the distribution of the error term.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Linear regression is widely used in biological, behavioral and social sciences to describe possible relationships between variables.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] It ranks as one of the most important tools used in these disciplines.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] A **trend line** represents a trend, the long-term movement in time series data after other components have been accounted for.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] It tells whether a particular data set (say GDP, oil prices or stock prices) have increased or decreased over the period of time.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] A trend line could simply be drawn by eye through a set of data points, but more properly their position and slope is calculated using statistical techniques like linear regression.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Trend lines typically are straight lines, although some variations use higher degree polynomials depending on the degree of curvature desired in the line.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Trend lines are sometimes used in business analytics to show changes in data over time.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Trend lines are often used to argue that a particular action or event (such as training, or an advertising campaign) caused observed changes at a point in time.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This is a simple technique, and does not require a control group, experimental design, or a sophisticated analysis technique.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] However, it suffers from a lack of scientific validity in cases where other potential changes can affect the data.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Early evidence relating tobacco smoking to mortality and morbidity came from observational studies employing regression analysis.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In order to reduce spurious correlations when analyzing observational data, researchers usually include several variables in their regression models in addition to the variable of primary interest.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] However, it is never possible to include all possible confounding variables in an empirical analysis.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] For example, a hypothetical gene might increase mortality and also cause people to smoke more.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] For this reason, randomized controlled trials are often able to generate more compelling evidence of causal relationships than can be obtained using regression analyses of observational data.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] When controlled experiments are not feasible, variants of regression analysis such as instrumental variables regression may be used to attempt to estimate causal relationships from observational data.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The capital asset pricing model uses linear regression as well as the concept of beta for analyzing and quantifying the systematic risk of an investment.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] This comes directly from the beta coefficient of the linear regression model that relates the return on the investment to the return on all risky assets.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Linear regression is the predominant empirical tool in economics.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] For example, it is used to predict consumption spending, fixed investment spending, inventory investment, purchases of a country's exports, spending on imports, the demand to hold liquid assets, labor demand, and labor supply.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Linear regression finds application in a wide range of environmental science applications such as land use, infectious diseases, and air pollution.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] For example, linear regression can be used to predict the changing effects of car pollution.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Linear regression is commonly used in building science field studies to derive characteristics of building occupants.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] In a thermal comfort field study, building scientists usually ask occupants' thermal sensation votes, which range from -3 (feeling cold) to 0 (neutral) to +3 (feeling hot), and measure occupants' surrounding temperature data.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] A neutral or comfort temperature can be calculated based on a linear regression between the thermal sensation vote and indoor temperature, and setting the thermal sensation vote as zero.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] However, there has been a debate on the regression direction: regressing thermal sensation votes (y-axis) against indoor temperature (x-axis) or the opposite: regressing indoor temperature (y-axis) against thermal sensation votes (x-axis).
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Linear regression plays an important role in the subfield of artificial intelligence known as machine learning.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The linear regression algorithm is one of the fundamental supervised machine-learning algorithms due to its relative simplicity and well-known properties.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Isaac Newton is credited with inventing "a certain technique known today as *linear regression analysis*" in his work on equinoxes in 1700, and wrote down the first of the two normal equations of the ordinary least squares method.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] The Least squares linear regression, as a means of finding a good rough linear fit to a set of points was performed by Legendre (1805) and Gauss (1809) for the prediction of planetary movement.
[src:linear-regression/linear-regression] Quetelet was responsible for making the procedure well-known and for using it extensively in the social sciences.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Some sources consider OLS to be linear regression.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Geometrically, this is seen as the sum of the squared distances, parallel to the axis of the dependent variable, between each data point in the set and the corresponding point on the regression surface—the smaller the differences, the better the model fits the data.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The resulting estimator can be expressed by a simple formula, especially in the case of a simple linear regression, in which there is a single regressor on the right side of the regression equation.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Under these conditions, the method of OLS provides minimum-variance mean-unbiased estimation when the errors have finite variances.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Under the additional assumption that the errors are normally distributed with zero mean, OLS is the maximum likelihood estimator that outperforms any non-linear unbiased estimator.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Each observation i includes a scalar response $y_{i}$ and a column vector $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ of p parameters (regressors), i.e., $\mathbf {x} _{i}=\left[x_{i1},x_{i2},\dots ,x_{ip}\right]^{\operatorname {T} }$ .
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Typically, a constant term is included in the set of regressors $\mathbf {X}$ , say, by taking $x_{i1}=1$ for all $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The coefficient $\beta _{1}$ corresponding to this regressor is called the *intercept*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Without the intercept, the fitted line is forced to cross the origin when $x_{i}={\vec {0}}$ .
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Regressors do not have to be independent for estimation to be consistent e.g. they may be non-linearly dependent.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Short of perfect multicollinearity, parameter estimates may still be consistent; however, as multicollinearity rises the standard error around such estimates increases and reduces the precision of such estimates.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] When there is perfect multicollinearity, it is no longer possible to obtain unique estimates for the coefficients to the related regressors; estimation for these parameters cannot converge (thus, it cannot be consistent).
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] As a concrete example where regressors are non-linearly dependent yet estimation may still be consistent, we might suspect the response depends linearly both on a value and its square; in which case we would include one regressor whose value is just the square of another regressor.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In that case, the model would be *quadratic* in the second regressor, but none-the-less is still considered a *linear* model because the model *is* still linear in the parameters ( ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ).
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] of n linear equations in p unknown coefficients, $\beta _{1},\beta _{2},\dots ,\beta _{p}$ , with $n>p$ .
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] (Note: for a linear model as above, not all elements in $\mathbf {X}$ contains information on the data points.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The first column is populated with ones, $X_{i1}=1$ .
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Only the other columns contain actual data.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] So here p is equal to the number of regressors plus one).
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] A justification for choosing this criterion is given in Properties below.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The matrix $\mathbf {X} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {X}$ is known as the *normal matrix* or Gram matrix and the matrix $\mathbf {X} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {y}$ is known as the moment matrix of regressand by regressors.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Suppose *b* is a "candidate" value for the parameter vector *β*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The quantity *yi* − *xi*T*b*, called the *residual* for the *i*-th observation, measures the vertical distance between the data point (*xi*, *yi*) and the hyperplane *y* = *x*T*b*, and thus assesses the degree of fit between the actual data and the model.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *T* denotes the matrix transpose, and the rows of *X*, denoting the values of all the independent variables associated with a particular value of the dependent variable, are *Xi = xi*T.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The value of *b* which minimizes this sum is called the **OLS estimator for *β***.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The product *N* = *X*T *X* is a Gram matrix, and its inverse, *Q* = *N*−1, is the *cofactor matrix* of *β*, closely related to its covariance matrix, *C**β*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The matrix (*X*T *X*)−1 *X*T = *Q* *X*T is called the Moore–Penrose pseudoinverse matrix of *X*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This formulation highlights the point that estimation can be carried out if, and only if, there is no perfect multicollinearity between the explanatory variables (which would cause the Gram matrix to have no inverse).
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *P* = *X*(*X*T*X*)−1*X*T is the *projection matrix* onto the space *V* spanned by the columns of *X*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This matrix *P* is also sometimes called the *hat matrix* because it "puts a hat" onto the variable *y*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Another matrix, closely related to *P* is the *annihilator* matrix *M* = *In* − *P*; this is a projection matrix onto the space orthogonal to *V*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Both matrices *P* and *M* are symmetric and idempotent (meaning that *P*2 = *P* and *M*2 = *M*), and relate to the data matrix *X* via identities *PX* = *X* and *MX* = 0.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *P* is the projection matrix and *s*2 is the sample variance.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *X*i is the *i*-th row of matrix *X*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The denominator, *n*−*p*, is the statistical degrees of freedom.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The first quantity, *s*2, is the OLS estimate for *σ*2, whereas the second, $\scriptstyle {\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ , is the MLE estimate for *σ*2.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The two estimators are quite similar in large samples; the first estimator is always unbiased, while the second estimator is biased but has a smaller mean squared error.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In practice *s*2 is used more often, since it is more convenient for the hypothesis testing.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The square root of *s*2 is called the *regression standard error*, *standard error of the regression*, or *standard error of the equation*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] It is common to assess the goodness-of-fit of the OLS regression by comparing how much the initial variation in the sample can be reduced by regressing onto *X*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where TSS is the *total sum of squares* for the dependent variable, ${\textstyle L=I_{n}-{\frac {1}{n}}J_{n}}$ , and ${\textstyle J_{n}}$ is an *n*×*n* matrix of ones.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In that case, *R*2 will always be a number between 0 and 1, with values close to 1 indicating a good degree of fit.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the data matrix *X* contains only two variables, a constant and a scalar regressor *xi*, then this is called the "simple regression model".
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This case is often considered in the beginner statistics classes, as it provides much simpler formulas even suitable for manual calculation.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In the previous section the least squares estimator ${\hat {\beta }}$ was obtained as a value that minimizes the sum of squared residuals of the model.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it is also possible to derive the same estimator from other approaches.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In all cases the formula for OLS estimator remains the same: ^*β* = (*X*T*X*)−1*X*T*y*; the only difference is in how we interpret this result.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] For mathematicians, OLS is an approximate solution to an overdetermined system of linear equations *Xβ* ≈ *y*, where *β* is the unknown.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Assuming the system cannot be solved exactly (the number of equations *n* is much larger than the number of unknowns *p*), we are looking for a solution that could provide the smallest discrepancy between the right- and left- hand sides.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where ‖·‖ is the standard *L*2 norm in the *n*-dimensional Euclidean space **R***n*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The predicted quantity *Xβ* is just a certain linear combination of the vectors of regressors.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Thus, the residual vector *y* − *Xβ* will have the smallest length when *y* is projected orthogonally onto the linear subspace spanned by the columns of *X*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The OLS estimator ${\hat {\beta }}$ in this case can be interpreted as the coefficients of vector decomposition of ^*y* = *Py* along the basis of *X*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This means that $\mathbf {y} -\mathbf {X} {\boldsymbol {\hat {\beta }}}$ is the shortest of all possible vectors $\mathbf {y} -\mathbf {X} {\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ , that is, the variance of the residuals is the minimum possible.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Introducing ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\gamma }}}$ and a matrix *K* with the assumption that a matrix $[\mathbf {X} \ \mathbf {K} ]$ is non-singular and *K*T *X* = 0 (cf.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Another way of looking at it is to consider the regression line to be a weighted average of the lines passing through the combination of any two points in the dataset.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Although this way of calculation is more computationally expensive, it provides a better intuition on OLS.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The OLS estimator is identical to the maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) under the normality assumption for the error terms.[proof] This normality assumption has historical importance, as it provided the basis for the early work in linear regression analysis by Yule and Pearson.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] From the properties of MLE, we can infer that the OLS estimator is asymptotically efficient (in the sense of attaining the Cramér–Rao bound for variance) if the normality assumption is satisfied.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] These moment conditions state that the regressors should be uncorrelated with the errors.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Since *xi* is a *p*-vector, the number of moment conditions is equal to the dimension of the parameter vector *β*, and thus the system is exactly identified.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This is the so-called classical GMM case, when the estimator does not depend on the choice of the weighting matrix.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Note that the original strict exogeneity assumption E[*εi* | *xi*] = 0 implies a far richer set of moment conditions than stated above.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In particular, this assumption implies that for any vector-function ƒ, the moment condition E[*ƒ*(*xi*)·*εi*] = 0 will hold.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it can be shown using the Gauss–Markov theorem that the optimal choice of function ƒ is to take *ƒ*(*x*) = *x*, which results in the moment equation posted above.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] There are several different frameworks in which the linear regression model can be cast in order to make the OLS technique applicable.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Each of these settings produces the same formulas and same results.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The only difference is the interpretation and the assumptions which have to be imposed in order for the method to give meaningful results.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The choice of the applicable framework depends mostly on the nature of data in hand, and on the inference task which has to be performed.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] One of the lines of difference in interpretation is whether to treat the regressors as random variables, or as predefined constants.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In the first case (**random design**) the regressors *xi* are random and sampled together with the *yi*'s from some population, as in an observational study.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This approach allows for more natural study of the asymptotic properties of the estimators.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In the other interpretation (**fixed design**), the regressors *X* are treated as known constants set by a design, and *y* is sampled conditionally on the values of *X* as in an experiment.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] For practical purposes, this distinction is often unimportant, since estimation and inference is carried out while conditioning on *X*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] All results stated in this article are within the random design framework.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The classical model focuses on the "finite sample" estimation and inference, meaning that the number of observations *n* is fixed.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This contrasts with the other approaches, which study the asymptotic behavior of OLS, and in which the behavior at a large number of samples is studied.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] To prove finite sample unbiasedness of the OLS estimator, we require the following assumptions.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Violations of these assumptions can result in biased estimations of ***β***, biased standard errors, untrustworthy confidence intervals and significance tests.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the strict exogeneity does not hold (as is the case with many time series models, where exogeneity is assumed only with respect to the past shocks but not the future ones), then these estimators will be biased in finite samples.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In particular, the standard error of each coefficient $\scriptstyle {\hat {\beta }}_{j}$ is equal to square root of the *j*-th diagonal element of this matrix.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The estimate of this standard error is obtained by replacing the unknown quantity *σ*2 with its estimate *s*2.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The *Gauss–Markov theorem* states that under the *spherical errors* assumption (that is, the errors should be uncorrelated and homoscedastic) the estimator $\scriptstyle {\hat {\beta }}$ is efficient in the class of linear unbiased estimators.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This is called the *best linear unbiased estimator* (BLUE).
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] in the sense that this is a nonnegative-definite matrix.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This theorem establishes optimality only in the class of linear unbiased estimators, which is quite restrictive.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Depending on the distribution of the error terms *ε*, other, non-linear estimators may provide better results than OLS.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The properties listed so far are all valid regardless of the underlying distribution of the error terms.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However, if you are willing to assume that the *normality assumption* holds (that is, that *ε* ~ *N*(0, *σ*2*In*)), then additional properties of the OLS estimators can be stated.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This estimator reaches the Cramér–Rao bound for the model, and thus is optimal in the class of all unbiased estimators.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Note that unlike the Gauss–Markov theorem, this result establishes optimality among both linear and non-linear estimators, but only in the case of normally distributed error terms.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The variance of this estimator is equal to 2*σ*4/(*n* − *p*), which does not attain the Cramér–Rao bound of 2*σ*4/*n*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it was shown that there are no unbiased estimators of *σ*2 with variance smaller than that of the estimator *s*2.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Moreover, the estimators $\scriptstyle {\hat {\beta }}$ and *s*2 are independent, the fact which comes in useful when constructing the t- and F-tests for the regression.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] As was mentioned before, the estimator ${\hat {\beta }}$ is linear in *y*, meaning that it represents a linear combination of the dependent variables *yi*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The weights in this linear combination are functions of the regressors *X*, and generally are unequal.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The observations with high weights are called **influential** because they have a more pronounced effect on the value of the estimator.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] To analyze which observations are influential we remove a specific *j*-th observation and consider how much the estimated quantities are going to change (similarly to the jackknife method).
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *hj* = *xj*T (*X*T*X*)−1*xj* is the *j*-th diagonal element of the hat matrix *P*, and *xj* is the vector of regressors corresponding to the *j*-th observation.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] From the properties of the hat matrix, 0 ≤ *hj* ≤ 1, and they sum up to *p*, so that on average *hj* ≈ *p/n*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] These quantities *hj* are called the **leverages**, and observations with high *hj* are called **leverage points**.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Usually the observations with high leverage ought to be scrutinized more carefully, in case they are erroneous, or outliers, or in some other way atypical of the rest of the dataset.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *M*1 is the annihilator matrix for regressors *X*1.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The theorem can be used to establish a number of theoretical results.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] For example, having a regression with a constant and another regressor is equivalent to subtracting the means from the dependent variable and the regressor and then running the regression for the de-meaned variables but without the constant term.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The least squares estimators are point estimates of the linear regression model parameters *β*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However, generally we also want to know how close those estimates might be to the true values of parameters.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In other words, we want to construct the interval estimates.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Since we have not made any assumption about the distribution of error term *εi*, it is impossible to infer the distribution of the estimators ${\hat {\beta }}$ and ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ .
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Nevertheless, we can apply the central limit theorem to derive their *asymptotic* properties as sample size *n* goes to infinity.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] While the sample size is necessarily finite, it is customary to assume that *n* is "large enough" so that the true distribution of the OLS estimator is close to its asymptotic limit.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *q* denotes the quantile function of standard normal distribution, and [·]*jj* is the *j*-th diagonal element of a matrix.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] These asymptotic distributions can be used for prediction, testing hypotheses, constructing other estimators, etc..
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] As an example consider the problem of prediction.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Suppose $x_{0}$ is some point within the domain of distribution of the regressors, and one wants to know what the response variable would have been at that point.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Two hypothesis tests are particularly widely used.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] First, one wants to know if the estimated regression equation is any better than simply predicting that all values of the response variable equal its sample mean (if not, it is said to have no explanatory power).
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The null hypothesis of no explanatory value of the estimated regression is tested using an F-test.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the calculated F-value is found to be large enough to exceed its critical value for the pre-chosen level of significance, the null hypothesis is rejected and the alternative hypothesis, that the regression has explanatory power, is accepted.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Otherwise, the null hypothesis of no explanatory power is accepted.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Second, for each explanatory variable of interest, one wants to know whether its estimated coefficient differs significantly from zero—that is, whether this particular explanatory variable in fact has explanatory power in predicting the response variable.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Here the null hypothesis is that the true coefficient is zero.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This hypothesis is tested by computing the coefficient's t-statistic, as the ratio of the coefficient estimate to its standard error.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the t-statistic is larger than a predetermined value, the null hypothesis is rejected and the variable is found to have explanatory power, with its coefficient significantly different from zero.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Otherwise, the null hypothesis of a zero value of the true coefficient is accepted.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In addition, the Chow test is used to test whether two subsamples both have the same underlying true coefficient values.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The sum of squared residuals of regressions on each of the subsets and on the combined data set are compared by computing an F-statistic; if this exceeds a critical value, the null hypothesis of no difference between the two subsets is rejected; otherwise, it is accepted.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In a time series model, we require the stochastic process {*xi*, *yi*} to be stationary and ergodic; if {*xi*, *yi*} is nonstationary, OLS results are often biased unless {*xi*, *yi*} is co-integrating.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] We still require the regressors to be *strictly exogenous*: E[*xiεi*] = 0 for all *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Finally, the assumptions on the variance take the form of requiring that {*xiεi*} is a martingale difference sequence, with a finite matrix of second moments *Q**xxε*² = E[ *εi*2*xi xi*T ].
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *Q* is a *p*×*q* matrix of full rank, and *c* is a *q*×1 vector of known constants, where *q < p*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In this case least squares estimation is equivalent to minimizing the sum of squared residuals of the model subject to the constraint *A*.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This expression for the constrained estimator is valid as long as the matrix *XTX* is invertible.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] It was assumed from the beginning of this article that this matrix is of full rank, and it was noted that when the rank condition fails, *β* will not be identifiable.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it may happen that adding the restriction *A* makes *β* identifiable, in which case one would like to find the formula for the estimator.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *R* is a *p*×(*p* − *q*) matrix such that the matrix [*Q R*] is non-singular, and *RTQ* = 0.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Such a matrix can always be found, although generally it is not unique.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The second formula coincides with the first in case when *XTX* is invertible.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The following data set gives average heights and weights for American women aged 30–39 (source: *The World Almanac and Book of Facts, 1975*).
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] When only one dependent variable is being modeled, a scatterplot will suggest the form and strength of the relationship between the dependent variable and regressors.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] It might also reveal outliers, heteroscedasticity, and other aspects of the data that may complicate the interpretation of a fitted regression model.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The scatterplot suggests that the relationship is strong and can be approximated as a quadratic function.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] OLS can handle non-linear relationships by introducing the regressor *HEIGHT*2.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Ordinary least squares analysis often includes the use of diagnostic plots designed to detect departures of the data from the assumed form of the model.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] An important consideration when carrying out statistical inference using regression models is how the data were sampled.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] In this example, the data are averages rather than measurements on individual women.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The fit of the model is very good, but this does not imply that the weight of an individual woman can be predicted with high accuracy based only on her height.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] This example also demonstrates that coefficients determined by these calculations are sensitive to how the data is prepared.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The heights were originally given rounded to the nearest inch and have been converted and rounded to the nearest centimetre.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Since the conversion factor is one inch to 2.54 cm this is *not* an exact conversion.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The original inches can be recovered by Round(x/0.0254) and then re-converted to metric without rounding.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Using either of these equations to predict the weight of a 5' 6" (1.6764 m) woman gives similar values: 62.94 kg with rounding vs.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Thus a seemingly small variation in the data has a real effect on the coefficients but a small effect on the results of the equation.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] While this may look innocuous in the middle of the data range it could become significant at the extremes or in the case where the fitted model is used to project outside the data range (extrapolation).
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] This highlights a common error: this example is an abuse of OLS which inherently requires that the errors in the independent variable (in this case height) are zero or at least negligible.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The initial rounding to nearest inch plus any actual measurement errors constitute a finite and non-negligible error.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] As a result, the fitted parameters are not the best estimates they are presumed to be.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Though not totally spurious the error in the estimation will depend upon relative size of the *x* and *y* errors.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] We can use the least square mechanism to figure out the equation of a two body orbit in polar base co-ordinates.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The equation typically used is $r(\theta )={\frac {p}{1-e\cos(\theta )}}$ where $r(\theta )$ is the radius of how far the object is from one of the bodies.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] In the equation the parameters p and e are used to determine the path of the orbit.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] We need to find the least-squares approximation of e and p for the given data.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] First we need to represent e and p in a linear form.
[src:linear-regression/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Furthermore, one could fit for apsides by expanding $\cos(\theta )$ with an extra parameter as $\cos(\theta -\theta _{0})=\cos(\theta )\cos(\theta _{0})+\sin(\theta )\sin(\theta _{0})$ , which is linear in both $\cos(\theta )$ and in the extra basis function $\sin(\theta )$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The most common form of regression analysis is linear regression, in which one finds the line (or a more complex linear combination) that most closely fits the data according to a specific mathematical criterion.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For example, the method of ordinary least squares computes the unique line (or hyperplane) that minimizes the sum of squared differences between the true data and that line (or hyperplane).
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For specific mathematical reasons (see linear regression), this allows the researcher to estimate the conditional expectation (or population average value) of the dependent variable when the independent variables take on a given set of values.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Less common forms of regression use slightly different procedures to estimate alternative location parameters (e.g., quantile regression or Necessary Condition Analysis) or estimate the conditional expectation across a broader collection of non-linear models (e.g., nonparametric regression).
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Regression analysis is primarily used for two conceptually distinct purposes.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] First, regression analysis is widely used for prediction and forecasting, where its use has substantial overlap with the field of machine learning.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Second, in some situations regression analysis can be used to infer causal relationships between the independent and dependent variables.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Importantly, regressions by themselves only reveal relationships between a dependent variable and a collection of independent variables in a fixed dataset.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] To use regressions for prediction or to infer causal relationships, respectively, a researcher must carefully justify why existing relationships have predictive power for a new context or why a relationship between two variables has a causal interpretation.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The latter is especially important when researchers hope to estimate causal relationships using observational data.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] He also distinguished between two inhomogeneous sets of data and might have thought of an *optimal* solution in terms of bias, though not in terms of effectiveness." He previously used an averaging method in his 1671 work on Newton's rings, which was unprecedented at the time.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The method of least squares was published by Legendre in 1805, and by Gauss in 1809.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Legendre and Gauss both applied the method to the problem of determining, from astronomical observations, the orbits of bodies about the Sun (mostly comets, but also later the then newly discovered minor planets).
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Gauss published a further development of the theory of least squares in 1821, including a version of the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The term "regression" was coined by Francis Galton in the 19th century to describe a biological phenomenon.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The phenomenon was that the heights of descendants of tall ancestors tend to regress down towards a normal average (a phenomenon also known as regression toward the mean).
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For Galton, regression had only this biological meaning, but his work was later extended by Udny Yule and Karl Pearson to a more general statistical context.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In the work of Yule and Pearson, the joint distribution of the response and explanatory variables is assumed to be Gaussian.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Fisher assumed that the conditional distribution of the response variable is Gaussian, but the joint distribution need not be.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In this respect, Fisher's assumption is closer to Gauss's formulation of 1821.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In the 1950s and 1960s, economists used electromechanical desk calculators to calculate regressions.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Before 1970, it sometimes took up to 24 hours to receive the result from one regression.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Regression methods continue to be an area of active research.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Modern regression analysis is typically done with statistical and spreadsheet software packages on computers as well as on handheld scientific and graphing calculators.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In practice, researchers first select a model they would like to estimate and then use their chosen method (e.g., ordinary least squares) to estimate the parameters of that model.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In various fields of application, different terminologies are used in place of dependent and independent variables.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In the standard regression model, the independent variables $X_{i}$ are assumed to be free of error.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The errors-in-variables model can be used if the independent variables are assumed to contain errors.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Other modifications to the standard regression model can be made to account for various scenarios, such as situations involving omitted variables, confounding variables or endogeneity.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The researchers' goal is to estimate the function $f(X_{i},\beta )$ that most closely fits the data.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] To carry out regression analysis, the form of the function f must be specified.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Sometimes the form of this function is based on knowledge about the relationship between $Y_{i}$ and $X_{i}$ that does not rely on the data.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] If no such knowledge is available, a flexible or convenient form for f is chosen.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For example, a simple univariate regression may propose $f(X_{i},\beta )=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}$ , suggesting that the researcher believes $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}+e_{i}$ to be a reasonable approximation for the statistical process generating the data.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Once researchers determine their preferred statistical model, different forms of regression analysis provide tools to estimate the parameters $\beta$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For example, least squares (including its most common variant, ordinary least squares) finds the value of $\beta$ that minimizes the sum of squared errors $\sum _{i}(Y_{i}-f(X_{i},\beta ))^{2}$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] A given regression method will ultimately provide an estimate of $\beta$ , usually denoted ${\hat {\beta }}$ to distinguish the estimate from the true (unknown) parameter value that generated the data.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Using this estimate, the researcher can then use the *fitted value* ${\hat {Y_{i}}}=f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ for prediction or to assess the accuracy of the model in explaining the data.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Whether the researcher is intrinsically interested in the estimate ${\hat {\beta }}$ or the predicted value ${\hat {Y_{i}}}$ will depend on context and their goals.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] As described in ordinary least squares, least squares is widely used because the estimated function $f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ approximates the conditional expectation $E(Y_{i}|X_{i})$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] However, alternative variants (e.g., least absolute deviations or quantile regression) are useful when researchers want to model other functions $f(X_{i},\beta )$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] There must be sufficient data to estimate a regression model.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For example, suppose that a researcher has access to N rows of data with one dependent and two independent variables: $(Y_{i},X_{1i},X_{2i})$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Suppose further that the researcher wants to estimate a bivariate linear model via least squares: $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{1i}+\beta _{2}X_{2i}+e_{i}$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] To understand why there are infinitely many options, note that the system of $N=2$ equations is to be solved for 3 unknowns, which makes the system underdetermined.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Alternatively, one can visualize infinitely many 3-dimensional planes that go through $N=2$ fixed points.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] More generally, to estimate a least squares model with k distinct parameters, one must have $N\geq k$ distinct data points.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] If $N>k$ , then there does not generally exist a set of parameters that will perfectly fit the data.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The quantity $N-k$ appears often in regression analysis, and is referred to as the degrees of freedom in the model.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Moreover, to estimate a least squares model, the independent variables $(X_{1i},X_{2i},...,X_{ki})$ must be linearly independent: one must *not* be able to reconstruct any of the independent variables by adding and multiplying the remaining independent variables.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] As discussed in ordinary least squares, this condition ensures that $X^{T}X$ is an invertible matrix and therefore that a unique solution ${\hat {\beta }}$ exists.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] By itself, a regression is just a computation performed on a set of data.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In order to interpret the resultant regression as a meaningful statistical model that quantifies real-world relationships, researchers often rely on a number of classical assumptions.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] A handful of conditions are sufficient for the least-squares estimator to possess desirable properties: in particular, the Gauss–Markov assumptions imply that the parameter estimates will be unbiased, consistent, and efficient in the class of linear unbiased estimators.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Practitioners have developed a variety of methods to maintain some or all of these desirable properties in real-world settings, because these classical assumptions are unlikely to hold exactly.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For example, modeling errors-in-variables can lead to reasonable estimates independent variables are measured with errors.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Heteroscedasticity-consistent standard errors allow the variance of $e_{i}$ to change across values of $X_{i}$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Correlated errors that exist within subsets of the data or follow specific patterns can be handled using *clustered standard errors, geographic weighted regression*, or Newey–West standard errors, among other techniques.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] When rows of data correspond to locations in space, the choice of how to model $e_{i}$ within geographic units can have important consequences.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The subfield of econometrics is largely focused on developing techniques that allow researchers to make reasonable real-world conclusions in real-world settings, where classical assumptions do not hold exactly.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In linear regression, the model specification is that the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ is a linear combination of the *parameters* (but need not be linear in the *independent variables*).
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In multiple linear regression, there are several independent variables or functions of independent variables.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In both cases, $\varepsilon _{i}$ is an error term and the subscript i indexes a particular observation.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The residual, $e_{i}=y_{i}-{\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , is the difference between the value of the dependent variable predicted by the model, ${\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , and the true value of the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] One method of estimation is ordinary least squares.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Minimization of this function results in a set of normal equations, a set of simultaneous linear equations in the parameters, which are solved to yield the parameter estimators, ${\widehat {\beta }}_{0},{\widehat {\beta }}_{1}$ .
