[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] This is called the mean square error (MSE) of the regression.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The denominator is the sample size reduced by the number of model parameters estimated from the same data, $(n-p)$ for p regressors or $(n-p-1)$ if an intercept is used.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] In this case, $p=1$ so the denominator is $n-2$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Under the further assumption that the population error term is normally distributed, the researcher can use these estimated standard errors to create confidence intervals and conduct hypothesis tests about the population parameters.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] where $x_{ij}$ is the i -th observation on the j -th independent variable.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] If the first independent variable takes the value 1 for all i , $x_{i1}=1$ , then $\beta _{1}$ is called the regression intercept.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The least squares parameter estimates are obtained from p normal equations.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] where the $ij$ element of $\mathbf {X}$ is $x_{ij}$ , the i element of the column vector Y is $y_{i}$ , and the j element of ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}$ is ${\hat {\beta }}_{j}$ .
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Once a regression model has been constructed, it may be important to confirm the goodness of fit of the model and the statistical significance of the estimated parameters.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Commonly used checks of goodness of fit include the R-squared, analyses of the pattern of residuals and hypothesis testing.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Statistical significance can be checked by an F-test of the overall fit, followed by t-tests of individual parameters.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Interpretations of these diagnostic tests rest heavily on the model's assumptions.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Although examination of the residuals can be used to invalidate a model, the results of a t-test or F-test are sometimes more difficult to interpret if the model's assumptions are violated.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For example, if the error term does not have a normal distribution, in small samples the estimated parameters will not follow normal distributions and complicate inference.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] With relatively large samples, however, a central limit theorem can be invoked such that hypothesis testing may proceed using asymptotic approximations.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Limited dependent variables, which are response variables that are categorical or constrained to fall only in a certain range, often arise in econometrics.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The response variable may be non-continuous ("limited" to lie on some subset of the real line).
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For binary (zero or one) variables, if analysis proceeds with least-squares linear regression, the model is called the linear probability model.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Nonlinear models for binary dependent variables include the probit and logit model.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The multivariate probit model is a standard method of estimating a joint relationship between several binary dependent variables and some independent variables.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For categorical variables with more than two values there is the multinomial logit.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For ordinal variables with more than two values, there are the ordered logit and ordered probit models.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Censored regression models may be used when the dependent variable is only sometimes observed, and Heckman correction type models may be used when the sample is not randomly selected from the population of interest.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] An alternative to such procedures is linear regression based on polychoric correlation (or polyserial correlations) between the categorical variables.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Such procedures differ in the assumptions made about the distribution of the variables in the population.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] If the variable is positive with low values and represents the repetition of the occurrence of an event, then count models like the Poisson regression or the negative binomial model may be used.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] When the model function is not linear in the parameters, the sum of squares must be minimized by an iterative procedure.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] This introduces many complications which are summarized in Differences between linear and non-linear least squares.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Regression models ***predict*** a value of the *Y* variable given known values of the *X* variables.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Prediction *within* the range of values in the dataset used for model-fitting is known informally as *interpolation*.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Prediction *outside* this range of the data is known as *extrapolation*.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Performing extrapolation relies strongly on the regression assumptions.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The further the extrapolation goes outside the data, the more room there is for the model to fail due to differences between the assumptions and the sample data or the true values.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] A *prediction interval* that represents the uncertainty may accompany the point prediction.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Such intervals tend to expand rapidly as the values of the independent variable(s) moved outside the range covered by the observed data.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For such reasons and others, some tend to say that it might be unwise to undertake extrapolation.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The assumption of a particular form for the relation between *Y* and *X* is another source of uncertainty.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] A properly conducted regression analysis will include an assessment of how well the assumed form is matched by the observed data, but it can only do so within the range of values of the independent variables actually available.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] This means that any extrapolation is particularly reliant on the assumptions being made about the structural form of the regression relationship.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] If this knowledge includes the fact that the dependent variable cannot go outside a certain range of values, this can be made use of in selecting the model – even if the observed dataset has no values particularly near such bounds.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] The implications of this step of choosing an appropriate functional form for the regression can be great when extrapolation is considered.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] At a minimum, it can ensure that any extrapolation arising from a fitted model is "realistic" (or in accord with what is known).
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] There are no generally agreed methods for relating the number of observations versus the number of independent variables in the model.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] One method conjectured by Good and Hardin is $N=m^{n}$ , where N is the sample size, n is the number of independent variables and m is the number of observations needed to reach the desired precision if the model had only one independent variable.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] For example, a researcher is building a linear regression model using a dataset that contains 1000 patients ( N ).
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] All major statistical software packages perform least squares regression analysis and inference.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Simple linear regression and multiple regression using least squares can be done in some spreadsheet applications and on some calculators.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] While many statistical software packages can perform various types of nonparametric and robust regression, these methods are less standardized.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Different software packages implement different methods, and a method with a given name may be implemented differently in different packages.
[src:linear-regression/regression-analysis] Specialized regression software has been developed for use in fields such as survey analysis and neuroimaging.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] In statistics, **simple linear regression** (**SLR**) is a linear regression model with a single explanatory variable.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The adjective *simple* refers to the fact that the outcome variable is related to a single predictor.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] In this case, the slope of the fitted line is equal to the correlation between y and x corrected by the ratio of standard deviations of these variables.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The intercept of the fitted line is such that the line passes through the center of mass (*x*, *y*) of the data points.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Consider the model function $y=\alpha +\beta x,$ which describes a line with slope β and y-intercept α.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] In general, such a relationship may not hold exactly for the largely unobserved population of values of the independent and dependent variables; we call the unobserved deviations from the above equation the errors.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] This relationship between the true (but unobserved) underlying parameters α and β and the data points is called a linear regression model.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The goal is to find estimated values ${\widehat {\alpha }}$ and ${\widehat {\beta }}$ for the parameters α and β which would provide the "best" fit in some sense for the data points.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The above equations are efficient to use if the mean of the x and y variables ( ${\bar {x}}{\text{ and }}{\bar {y}}$ ) are known.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] If the means are not known at the time of calculation, it may be more efficient to use the expanded version of the ${\widehat {\alpha }}{\text{ and }}{\widehat {\beta }}$ equations.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] These expanded equations may be derived from the more general polynomial regression equations by defining the regression polynomial to be of order 1, as follows.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The above system of linear equations may be solved directly, or stand-alone equations for ${\widehat {\alpha }}{\text{ and }}{\widehat {\beta }}$ may be derived by expanding the matrix equations above.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The resultant equations are algebraically equivalent to the ones shown in the prior paragraph, and are shown below without proof.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] This shows that *r**xy* is the slope of the regression line of the standardized data points (and that this line passes through the origin).
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Since $-1\leq r_{xy}\leq 1$ then we get that if x is some measurement and y is a followup measurement from the same item, then we expect that y (on average) will be closer to the mean measurement than it was to the original value of x.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] This phenomenon is known as regressions toward the mean.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Generalizing the ${\bar {x}}$ notation, we can write a horizontal bar over an expression to indicate the average value of that expression over the set of samples.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The coefficient of determination ("R squared") is equal to $r_{xy}^{2}$ when the model is linear with a single independent variable.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] See sample correlation coefficient for additional details.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The parameter ${\widehat {\alpha }}$ is the intercept of the linear function ${\begin{aligned}{y}&={\widehat {\alpha }}\ +{\widehat {\beta }}\,{x},\\[5pt]\end{aligned}}$ .
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Because ${\widehat {\beta }}$ is the slope of the linear function, ${\widehat {\beta }}=\tan(\theta )$ .
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] In the above formulation, notice that each $x_{i}$ is a constant ("known upfront") value, while the $y_{i}$ are random variables that depend on the linear function of $x_{i}$ and the random term $\varepsilon _{i}$ .
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] This assumption is used when deriving the standard error of the slope and showing that it is unbiased.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] In this framing, when $x_{i}$ is not actually a random variable, what type of parameter does the empirical correlation $r_{xy}$ estimate?
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The issue is that for each value i we'll have: $E(x_{i})=x_{i}$ and $Var(x_{i})=0$ .
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] A possible interpretation of $r_{xy}$ is to imagine that $x_{i}$ defines a random variable drawn from the empirical distribution of the x values in our sample.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] For example, if x had 10 values from the natural numbers: [1,2,3...,10], then we can imagine x to be a Discrete uniform distribution.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Under this interpretation all $x_{i}$ have the same expectation and some positive variance.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] With this interpretation we can think of $r_{xy}$ as the estimator of the Pearson's correlation between the random variable y and the random variable x (as we just defined it).
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Description of the statistical properties of estimators from the simple linear regression estimates requires the use of a statistical model.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The following is based on assuming the validity of a model under which the estimates are optimal.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] It is also possible to evaluate the properties under other assumptions, such as inhomogeneity, but this is discussed elsewhere.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The estimators ${\widehat {\alpha }}$ and ${\widehat {\beta }}$ are unbiased.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] To formalize this assertion we must define a framework in which these estimators are random variables.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] We consider the residuals *ε*i as random variables drawn independently from some distribution with mean zero.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] In other words, for each value of x, the corresponding value of y is generated as a mean response *α* + *βx* plus an additional random variable ε called the *error term*, equal to zero on average.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Under such interpretation, the least-squares estimators ${\widehat {\alpha }}$ and ${\widehat {\beta }}$ will themselves be random variables whose means will equal the "true values" α and β.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] This is the definition of an unbiased estimator.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Since the data in this context is defined to be (*x*, *y*) pairs for every observation, the *mean response* at a given value of *x*, say *xd*, is an estimate of the mean of the *y* values in the population at the *x* value of *xd*, that is ${\hat {E}}(y\mid x_{d})\equiv {\hat {y}}_{d}\!$ .
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The *predicted response* distribution is the predicted distribution of the residuals at the given point *xd*.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The second line follows from the fact that $\operatorname {Cov} \left(y_{d},\left[{\hat {\alpha }}+{\hat {\beta }}x_{d}\right]\right)$ is zero because the new prediction point is independent of the data used to fit the model.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Additionally, the term $\operatorname {Var} \left({\hat {\alpha }}+{\hat {\beta }}x_{d}\right)$ was calculated earlier for the mean response.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The formulas given in the previous section allow one to calculate the *point estimates* of α and β — that is, the coefficients of the regression line for the given set of data.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] However, those formulas do not tell us how precise the estimates are, i.e., how much the estimators ${\widehat {\alpha }}$ and ${\widehat {\beta }}$ vary from sample to sample for the specified sample size.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Confidence intervals were devised to give a plausible set of values to the estimates one might have if one repeated the experiment a very large number of times.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] 2. the number of observations n is sufficiently large, in which case the estimator is approximately normally distributed.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The latter case is justified by the central limit theorem.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] At the same time the sum of squared residuals Q is distributed proportionally to *χ*2 with *n* − 2 degrees of freedom, and independently from ${\widehat {\beta }}$ .
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] is the unbiased *standard error* estimator of the estimator ${\widehat {\beta }}$ .
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] This t-value has a Student's t-distribution with *n* − 2 degrees of freedom.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] For example, if *γ* = 0.05 then the confidence level is 95%.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The confidence intervals for α and β give us the general idea where these regression coefficients are most likely to be.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] In order to represent this information graphically, in the form of the confidence bands around the regression line, one has to proceed carefully and account for the joint distribution of the estimators.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] The alternative second assumption states that when the number of points in the dataset is "large enough", the law of large numbers and the central limit theorem become applicable, and then the distribution of the estimators is approximately normal.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Under this assumption all formulas derived in the previous section remain valid, with the only exception that the quantile *t***n*−2 of Student's *t* distribution is replaced with the quantile *q** of the standard normal distribution.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Occasionally the fraction ⁠1/*n*−2⁠ is replaced with ⁠1/*n*⁠.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] When n is large such a change does not alter the results appreciably.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] This data set gives average masses for women as a function of their height in a sample of American women of age 30–39.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Although the OLS article argues that it would be more appropriate to run a quadratic regression for this data, the simple linear regression model is applied here instead.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] There are *n* = 15 points in this data set.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] These quantities would be used to calculate the estimates of the regression coefficients, and their standard errors.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] In SLR, there is an underlying assumption that only the dependent variable contains measurement error; if the explanatory variable is also measured with error, then simple regression is not appropriate for estimating the underlying relationship because it will be biased due to regression dilution.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Other estimation methods that can be used in place of ordinary least squares include least absolute deviations (minimizing the sum of absolute values of residuals) and the Theil–Sen estimator (which chooses a line whose slope is the median of the slopes determined by pairs of sample points).
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Line fitting is the process of constructing a straight line that has the best fit to a series of data points.
[src:linear-regression/simple-linear-regression] Sometimes it is appropriate to force the regression line to pass through the origin, because x and y are assumed to be proportional.
